120. velati limo] All Mss. give lino, ‘ in linen,' but Servius states that before his time eritics had pointed out that the true reading was limo, and says that limus was an apron, so- called from a eross-stripe of purple (purpura lima), used by attendants on magistrates, ete, though Gellius derives the word from its being worn ‘cross-wise.' virgil is very fond of using arehaic and antiquarian words, and a rare word like this would almost certainly be corrupted by copyists. For tempora vincti see 172 n.
